Hi,

I have recently done a small hack for my custom notebook app, and I think it might be of interest for the community. Essentially, I have inserted a **run** / **stop** button in the `input_prompt` area of every code cell. Here what it looks like:

![screen shot 2017-05-30 at 14 36 10](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/8419388/26599119/77d47c5a-4545-11e7-80c2-a7f67fee8c81.png)

Instead of writing `in: [n]`, where _n_ is the execution rank, I write _n_ followed by a clickable button that calls the notebook's `execute_selected_cell` method. And while running the cell, instead of changing the value to a **star** between the brackets (which is far from intuitive or visible), I modify the button and change its color:

![screen shot 2017-05-30 at 14 36 36](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/8419388/26599128/7f19f706-4545-11e7-8356-db3b2ec31015.png)

I think that this interface is much much more ergonomic than the default one, especially for (young) users who are not inclined to use the keyboard (not necessarily my case, but definitely the case of most of my first year students who are learning Python using notebooks). It minimizes both the number of clicks and mouse travel! The only downside is that users may no longer feel the need to learn keyboard shortcuts ;-)

Here is the `custom.js` snippet to achieve this:
```
function execute_selected_cell() {
    require(['base/js/namespace'], function (jupyter) {
        jupyter.notebook.execute_selected_cells();
    });
}

function interrupt_kernel() {
    require(['base/js/namespace'], function (jupyter) {
        jupyter.notebook.kernel.interrupt();
    });
}

define(['base/js/namespace', 'base/js/events', 'notebook/js/codecell'], function (jupyter, events, cell) {
    cell.CodeCell.input_prompt_function = function (value, lines_number) {
        if (value === undefined || value === null) {
            return '<button class="btn btn-default btn-sm" onclick="execute_selected_cell()" title="exécuter la cellule"><i class="fa fa-play"></i></button>&nbsp;';
        } else if(value === '*') {
            return '<button class="btn btn-danger btn-sm" onclick="interrupt_kernel()" title="stopper l\'exécution">stop <i class="fa fa-stop"></i></button>&nbsp;';
        } else {
            return '<button class="btn btn-default btn-sm" onclick="execute_selected_cell()" title="exécuter la cellule">' + value + '&nbsp;<i class="fa fa-play"></i></button>&nbsp;';
        }
    };
});
```
(I don't master the define / require calls, not sure which is needed where, but the above code works; feel free to tell me how it can be made cleaner)

What do you think?

